h Night (Northern Ireland)\nBULLET::::- Free Slurpee Day (Participating stores of the 7-Eleven chain in North America)\nBULLET::::- National Day of Remembrance of Victims of Genocide by Ukrainian Nationalists on Citizens of the Second Republic of Poland (Poland)\nBULLET::::- Gospel Day (Kiribati)\nBULLET::::- Imamat Day (Isma'ilism)\nBULLET::::- National Day of Commemoration, held on the nearest Sunday to this date (Ireland)\nBULLET::::- The first day of Naadam (July 11–15) (Mongolia)\nBULLET::::- World Population Day (International)\n\nBULLET::::- BBC: On This Day\nBULLET::::- On This Day in Canada\n"}
{"id": "15874", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=15874", "title": "July 8", "text": "July 8\n\nBULLET::::- 1099 – Some 15,000 starving Christian soldiers begin the siege of Jerusalem by marching in a religious procession around the city as its Muslim defenders watch.\nBULLET::::- 1283 – Roger of Lauria, commanding the Aragonese fleet defeats an Angevin fleet sent to put down a rebellion on Malta.\nBULLET::::- 1497 – Vasco da Gama sets sail on the first direct European voyage to India.\nBULLET::::- 1579 – Our Lady of Kazan, a holy icon of the Russian Orthodox Church, is discovered underground in the city of Kazan, Tatarstan.\nBULLET::::- 1663 – Charles II of England grants John Clarke a Royal charter to Rhode Island.\nBULLET::::- 1709 – Peter I of Russia defeats Charles XII of Sweden at the Battle of Poltava, thus effectively ending Sweden's status as a major power in Europe.\nBULLET::::- 1716 – The Battle of Dynekilen forces Sweden to abandon its invasion of Norway.\nBULLET::::- 1730 – An estimated magnitude 8.7 earthquake causes a tsunami that damages more than of Chile's coastline.\nBULLET::::- 1758 – French forces hold Fort Carillon against the British at Ticonderoga, New York.\nBULLET::::- 1760 – British forces defeat French forces in the last naval battle in New France.\nBULLET::::- 1775 – The Olive Branch Petition is signed by the Continental Congress of the Thirteen Colonies of North America.\nBULLET::::- 1776 – Church bells (possibly including the Liberty Bell) are rung after John Nixon delivers the first public reading of the Declaration of Independence of the United States.\nBULLET::::- 1808 – Joseph Bonaparte approves the Bayonne Statute, a royal charter intended as the basis for his rule as king of Spain.\nBULLET::::- 1822 – Chippewas turn over a huge tract of land in Ontario to the United Kingdom.\nBULLET::::- 1853 – The Perry Expedition arrives in Edo Bay with a treaty requesting trade.\nBULLET::::- 1859 – King Charles XV & IV accedes to the throne of Sweden–Norway.\nBULLET::::- 1864 – Ikedaya Incident: The Choshu Han shishi's planned Shinsengumi sabotage on Kyoto, Japan at Ikedaya.\nBULLET::::- 1874 – The Mounties begin their March West.\nBULLET::::- 1876 – White supremacists kill five Black Republicans in Hamburg, South Carolina.\nBULLET::::- 1879 – Sailing ship departs San Francisco carrying an ill-fated expedition to the North Pole.\nBULLET::::- 1889 – The first issue of \"The Wall Street Journal\" is published.\nBULLET::::- 1892 – St. John's, Newfoundland is devastated in the Great Fire of 1892.\nBULLET::::- 1898 – The death of crime boss Soapy Smith, killed in the Shootout on Juneau Wharf, releases Skagway, Alaska from his iron grip.\nBULLET::::- 1912 – Henrique Mitchell de Paiva Couceiro leads an unsuccessful royalist attack against the First Portuguese Republic in Chaves.\nBULLET::::- 1932 – The Dow Jones Industrial Average reaches its lowest level of the Great Depression, closing at 41.22.\nBULLET::::- 1933 – The first rugby union test match between the Wallabies of Australia and the Springboks of South Africa is played at Newlands Stadium in Cape Town.\nBULLET::::- 1937 – Turkey, Iran, Iraq and Afghanistan sign the Treaty of Saadabad.\nBULLET::::- 1947 – Reports are broadcast that a UFO crash landed in Roswell, New Mexico in what became known as the Roswell UFO incident.\nBULLET::::- 1948 – The United States Air Force accepts its first female recruits into a program called Women in the Air Force (WAF).\nBULLET::::- 1960 – Francis Gary Powers is charged with espionage resulting from his flight over the Soviet Union.\nBULLET::::- 1962 – Ne Win besieges and dynamites the Rangoon University Student Union building to crush the Student Movement.\nBULLET::::- 1966 – King Mwambutsa IV Bangiriceng of Burundi is deposed by his son Prince Charles Ndizi.\nBULLET::::- 1968 – The Chrysler wildcat strike begins in Detroit, Michigan.\nBULLET::::- 1970 – Richard Nixon delivers a special congressional message enunciating Native American self-determination as official US Indian policy, leading to the Indian Self-Determination and Education Assistance Act of 1975.\nBULLET::::- 1972 – Israeli Mossad assassinate Palestinian writer Ghassan Kanafani.\nBULLET::::- 1980 – The inaugural 1980 State of Origin game is won by Queensland who defeat New South Wales 20-10 at Lang Park.\nBULLET::::- 1982 – Assassination attempt against Iraqi president Saddam Hussein in Dujail.\nBULLET::::- 1988 – The Island Express train travelling from Bangalore to Kanyakumari derails on the Peruman bridge and falls into Ashtamudi Lake, killing 105 passengers and injuring over 200 more.\nBULLET::::- 1994 – Kim Jong-il begins to assume supreme leadership of North Korea upon the death of his father, Kim Il-sung.\nBULLET::::- 2003 – Sudan Airways Flight 139 crashes near Port Sudan Airport during an emergency landing attempt, killing all 117 people on board.\nBULLET::::- 2011 – Space Shuttle \"Atlantis\" is launched in the final mission of the U.S. Space Shuttle program.\nBULLET::::- 2014 – Israel launches an offensive on Gaza amid rising tensions following the kidnapping and murder of three Israeli teenagers.\n\nBULLET::::- 1478 – Gian Giorgio Trissino, Italian linguist, poet, and playwright (d. 1550)\nBULLET::::- 1528 – Emmanuel Philibert, Duke of Savoy (d. 1580)\nBULLET::::- 1538 – Alberto Bolognetti, Roman Catholic cardinal (d. 1585)\nBULLET::::- 1545 – Carlos, Prince of Asturias (d. 1568)\nBULLET::::- 1593 – Artemisia Gentileschi, Italian painter (d. 1653)\nBULLET::::- 1593 – Peter Sainthill, English politician (d. 1648)\nBULLET::::- 1621 – Jean de La Fontaine, French author and poet (d. 1695)\nBULLET::::- 1760 – Christian Kramp, French mathematician and academic (d. 1826)\nBULLET::::- 1766 – Dominique Jean Larrey, French surgeon (d. 1842)\nBULLET::::- 1779 – Giorgio Pullicino, Maltese painter and architect (d. 1851)\nBULLET::::- 1819 – Francis Leopold McClintock, Irish admiral and explorer (d. 1907)\n