rouac's Town\". Creative Arts, 1977.\nBULLET::::- Gifford, Barry; Lee, Lawrence. \"Jack's Book: An Oral Biography of Jack Kerouac\". St. Martin's Press, 1978.\nBULLET::::- Grace, Nancy M. Jack Kerouac and the Literary Imagination. Palgrave-macmillan, 2007.\nBULLET::::- Goldstein, N.W., \"Kerouac's \"On the Road\". Explicator 50.1. 1991.\nBULLET::::- Haynes, Sarah, \"An Exploration of Jack Kerouac's Buddhism:Text and Life\"\nBULLET::::- Hemmer, Kurt. \"Encyclopedia of Beat Literature: The Essential Guide to the Lives and Works of the Beat Writers\". Facts on File, Inc., 2007.\nBULLET::::- Hipkiss, Robert A., \"Jack Kerouac: Prophet of the New Romanticism\". Regents Press, 1976.\nBULLET::::- Holmes, John Clellon. \"Visitor: Jack Kerouac in Old Saybrook\". tuvoti, 1981.\nBULLET::::- Holmes, John Clellon. \"Gone In October: Last Reflections on Jack Kerouac\". Limberlost, 1985.\nBULLET::::- Holton, Robert. \"On the Road: Kerouac's Ragged American Journey\". Twayne, 1999.\nBULLET::::- Hrebeniak, Michael. \"Action Writing: Jack Kerouac\"s Wild Form\". Carbondale IL., Southern Illinois UP, 2006.\nBULLET::::- Huebel, Harry Russell. \"Jack Kerouac\". Boise State University, 1979.available online\nBULLET::::- Hunt, Tim. \"Kerouac's Crooked Road\". Hamden: Archon Books, 1981.\nBULLET::::- Jarvis, Charles. \"Visions of Kerouac\". Ithaca Press, 1973.\nBULLET::::- Johnson, Joyce. \"Minor Characters: A Young Woman's Coming-Of-Age in the Beat Orbit of Jack Kerouac\". Penguin Books, 1999.\nBULLET::::- Johnson, Joyce. \"Door Wide Open: A Beat Love Affair in Letters, 1957–1958\". Viking, 2000.\nBULLET::::- Johnson, Ronna C., \"You're Putting Me On: Jack Kerouac and the Postmodern Emergence\". College Literature. 27.1 2000.\nBULLET::::- Jones, James T., \"A Map of Mexico City Blues: Jack Kerouac as Poet\". Southern Illinois University Press, 1992.\nBULLET::::- Jones, James T., \"Jack Kerouac's Duluoz Legend\". Carbondale: Southern Illinois University Press, 1999.\nBULLET::::- Jones, Jim. \"Use My Name: Kerouac's Forgotten Families\". ECW Press, 1999.\nBULLET::::- Jones, Jim. \"Jack Kerouac's Nine Lives\". Elbow/Cityful Press, 2001.\nBULLET::::- Kealing, Bob. \"Kerouac in Florida: Where the Road Ends\". Arbiter Press, 2004.\nBULLET::::- Kerouac, Joan Haverty. \"Nobody's Wife: The Smart Aleck and the King of the Beats\". Creative Arts, 2000.\nBULLET::::- Landefeld, Kurt. \"Jack's Memoirs: Off the Road, A Novel\". Bottom Dog Press, 2014.\nBULLET::::- Le Bihan, Adrien. \"Mon frère, Jack Kerouac\", Le temps qu'il fait, 2018. ()\nBULLET::::- Leland, John. \"Why Kerouac Matters: The Lessons of On the Road (They're Not What You Think)\". New York: Viking Press, 2007. .\nBULLET::::- Maher Jr., Paul. \"Kerouac: His Life and Work\". Lanham: Taylor Trade P, July 2004\nBULLET::::- McNally, Dennis. \"Desolate Angel: Jack Kerouac, the Beat Generation, and America\". Da Capo Press, 2003.\nBULLET::::- Montgomery, John. \"Jack Kerouac: A Memoir ... \" Giligia Press, 1970.\nBULLET::::- Montgomery, John. \"Kerouac West Coast\". Fels & Firn Press, 1976.\nBULLET::::- Montgomery, John. \"The Kerouac We Knew\". Fels & Firn Press, 1982.\nBULLET::::- Montgomery, John. \"Kerouac at the Wild Boar\". Fels & Firn Press, 1986.\nBULLET::::- Mortenson, Erik R., \"Beating Time: Configurations of Temporality in Jack Kerouac's On the Road\". College Literature 28.3. 2001.\nBULLET::::- Motier, Donald. \"Gerard: The Influence of Jack Kerouac's Brother on his Life and Writing\". Beaulieu Street Press, 1991.\nBULLET::::- Nelson, Victoria. \"Dark Journey into Light: On the Road with Jack Kerouac\". \"Saint Austin Review\" (November/December 2014).\nBULLET::::- Nicosia, Gerald. \"Kerouac: The Last Quarter Century\" Noodlebrain Press, 2019.\nBULLET::::- Nicosia, Gerald. \"Memory Babe: A Critical Biography of Jack Kerouac\" Grove Press, 1983.\nBULLET::::- Nicosia, Gerald. \"One and Only: The Untold Story of On the Road\" Viva Editions, 2011.\nBULLET::::- Parker, Brad. \"\"Jack Kerouac: An Introduction\"\". Lowell Corporation for the Humanities, 1989.\nBULLET::::- Swick, Thomas. \"South Florida Sun Sentinel\". February 22, 2004. Article: \"Jack Kerouac in Orlando\".\nBULLET::::- Theado, Matt. \"Understanding Jack Kerouac\". Columbia: University of South Carolina, 2000.\nBULLET::::- Turner, Steve. \"Angelheaded Hipster: A Life of Jack Kerouac\". Viking Books, 1996.\nBULLET::::- Walsh, Joy, editor. \"Moody Street Irregulars: A Jack Kerouac Newsletter\"\nBULLET::::- Weaver, Helen. \"The Awakener: A Memoir of Jack Kerouac and the Fifties\". City Lights, 2009. . .\nBULLET::::- Weinreich, Regina. \"The Spontaneous Poetics of Jack Kerouac\". Southern Illinois University Press, 1987.\nBULLET::::- Wills, David, editor. \"Beatdom\" Magazine. Mauling Press, 2007.\nAnctil, Gabriel and Pleau, Jean-Philippe. \"Sur les traces de Kerouac\", 4 x 1 hour, 2015 . \n\nBULLET::::- Kerouac.net—An introduction to the life and work of Jack Kerouac, and the deep impact he had on our society and culture.\nBULLET::::- JackKerouac.com – The Jack and Stella Kerouac Center for the Public Humanities's website is an interactive storehouse and exhibition space dedicated to Jack Kerouac and connected topics.\nBULLET::::- Jack Kerouac Papers at the Rare Book & Manuscript Library at Columbia University\nBULLET::::- Jack Kerouac Papers, 1920–1977, held by the Henry W. and Albert A. Berg Collection of English and American Literature, New York Public Library\nBULLET::::- \"Writings of Jack Kerouac\" from C-SPAN's \"\"\nBULLET::::- The Kerouac Companion—The definitive key to the 600+ characters in Kerouac's novels.\nBULLET::::- \"sur-les-traces-de-kerouac\" Radio documentary on Radio-Canada (2015)\nBULLET::::- \"sur-les-traces-de-kerouac\" ebook by Gabriel Anctil & Marie-Sandrine Auger\n"}
{"id": "15892", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=15892", "title": "July 26", "text": "July 26\n\nBULLET::::- 657 – First Fitna: In the Battle of Siffin, troops led by Ali ibn Abu Talib clash with those led by Muawiyah I.\nBULLET::::- 811 – Battle of Pliska: Byzantine Emperor Nikephoros I is killed and his heir Staurakios is seriously wounded.\nBULLET::::- 920 – Rout of an alliance of Christian troops from Navarre and Léon against the Muslims at the Battle of Valdejunquera.\nBULLET::::- 1309 – Henry VII is recognized King of the Romans by Pope Clement V.\nBULLET::::- 1469 – Wars of the Roses: The Battle of Edgecote Moor, pitting the forces of Richard Neville, 16th Earl of Warwick against those of Edward IV of England, takes place.\nBULLET::::- 1509 – The Emperor Krishnadevaraya ascends to the throne, marking the beginning of the regeneration of the Vijayanagara Empire.\nBULLET::::- 1529 – Francisco Pizarro González, Spanish conquistador, is appointed governor of Peru.\nBULLET::::- 1581 – Plakkaat van Verlatinghe (Act of Abjuration): The northern Low Countries declare their independence from the Spanish king, Philip II.\nBULLET::::- 1703 – During the \"Bavarian Rummel\" the rural population of Tyrol drove the Bavarian Prince-Elector Maximilian II Emanuel out of North Tyrol with a victory at the Pontlatzer Bridge and thus prevented the Bavarian Army, which was allied with France, from marching as planned on Vienna during the War of the Spanish Succession.\nBULLET::::- 1745 – The first recorded women's cricket match takes place near Guildford, England.\nBULLET::::- 1758 – French and Indian War: The Siege of Louisbourg ends with British forces defeating the French and taking control of the Gulf of Saint Lawrence.\nBULLET::::- 1775 – The office that would later become the United States Post Office Department is established by the Second Continental Congress. Benjamin Franklin of Pennsylvania takes office as Postmaster General.\nBULLET::::- 1788 – New York ratifies the United States Constitution and becomes the 11th state of the United States.\nBULLET::::- 1803 – The Surrey Iron Railway, arguably the world's first public railway, opens in south London, United Kingdom.\nBULLET::::- 1814 – The Swedish–Norwegian War begins.\nBULLET::::- 1822 – José de San Martín arrives in Guayaquil, Ecuador, to meet with Simón Bolívar.\nBULLET::::- 1822 – First day of the three-day Battle of Dervenakia, between the Ottoman Empire force led by Mahmud Dramali Pasha and the Greek Revolutionary force led by Theodoros Kolokotronis.\nBULLET::::- 1847 – Liberia declares its independence.\nBULLET::::- 1861 – American Civil War: George B. McClellan assumes command of the Army of the Potomac following a disastrous Union defeat at the First Battle of Bull Run.\nBULLET::::- 1863 – American Civil War: Morgan's Raid ends; At Salineville, Ohio, Confederate cavalry leader John Hunt Morgan and 360 of his volunteers are captured by Union forces.\nBULLET::::- 1882 – Premiere of Richard Wagner's opera \"Parsifal\" at Bayreuth.\nBULLET::::- 1882 – The Republic of Stellaland is founded in Southern Africa.\nBULLET::::- 1887 – Publication of the \"Unua Libro\", founding the Esperanto movement.\nBULLET::::- 1890 – In Buenos Aires, Argentina the Revolución del Parque takes place, forcing President Miguel Ángel Juárez Celman's resignation.\nBULLET::::- 1891 – France annexes Tahiti.\nBULLET::::- 1892 – Dadabhai Naoroji is elected as the first Indian Member of Parliament in Britain.\nBULLET::::- 1897 – Anglo-Afghan War: The Pashtun fakir Saidullah leads an army of more than 10,000 to begin a siege of the British garrison in the Malakand Agency of the North West Frontier Province of India.\nBULLET::::- 1899 – Ulises Heureaux, the 27th President of the Dominican Republic, is assassinated.\nBULLET::::- 1908 – United States Attorney General Charles Joseph Bonaparte issues an order to immediately staff the Office of the Chief Examiner (later renamed the Federal Bureau of Investigation).\nBULLET::::- 1918 – Emmy Noether's paper, which became known as Noether's theorem was presented at Göttingen, Germany, from which conservation laws are deduced for symmetries of angular momentum, linear momentum, and energy.\nBULLET::::- 1936 – Spanish Civil War: Germany and Italy decide to intervene in the war in support for Francisco Franco and the Nationalist faction.\nBULLET::::- 1936 – King Edward VIII, in one of his few official duties before he abdicates the throne, officially unveils the Canadian National Vimy Memorial.\nBULLET::::- 1937 – Spanish Civil War: End of the Battle of Brunete with the Nationalist victory.\nBULLET::::- 1941 – World War II: In response to the Japanese occupation of French Indochina, the United States, Britain and the Netherlands freeze all Japanese assets and cut off oil shipments.\nBULLET::::- 1944 – World War II: The Red Army enters Lviv, a major city in western Ukraine, capturing it from the Nazis. Only 300 Jews survive out of 160,000 living in Lviv prior to occupation.\nBULLET::::- 1945 – The Labour Party wins the United Kingdom general election of July 5 by a landslide, removing Winston Churchill from power.\nBULLET::::- 1945 – World War II: The Potsdam Declaration is signed in Potsdam, Germany.\nBULLET::::- 1945 – World War II: is the last British Royal Navy ship to be sunk in the war.\nBULLET::::- 1945 – World War II: The arrives at Tinian with components and enriched uranium for the Little Boy nuclear bomb.\nBULLET::::- 1946 – Aloha Airlines begins service from Honolulu International Airport.\nBULLET::::- 1947 – Cold War: U.S. President Harry S. Truman signs the National Security Act of 1947 into United States law creating the Central Intelligence Agency, United States Department of Defense, United States Air Force, Joint Chiefs of Staff, and the United States National Security Council.\nBULLET::::- 1948 – U.S. President Harry S. Truman signs Executive Order 9981, desegregating the military of the United States.\nBULLET::::- 1951 – Walt Disney's 13th animated film, \"Alice in Wonderland\", premieres in London, England, United Kingdom.\nBULLET::::- 1952 – King Farouk of Egypt abdicates in favor of his son Fuad.\nBULLET::::- 1953 – Cold War: Fidel Castro leads an unsuccessful attack on the Moncada Barracks, thus beginning the Cuban Revolution. The movement took the name of the date: 26th of July Movement\nBULLET::::- 1953 – Arizona Governor John Howard Pyle orders an anti-polygamy law enforcement crackdown on residents of Short Creek, Arizona, which becomes known as the Short Creek raid.\nBULLET::::- 1953 – Soldiers from the 2nd Battalion, Royal Australian Regiment repel a number of Chinese assaults against a key position known as The Hook during the Battle of the Samichon River, just hours before the Armistice Agreement is signed, ending the Korean War.\nBULLET::::- 1956 – Following the World Bank's refusal to fund building the Aswan Dam, Egyptian leader Gamal Abdel Nasser nationalizes the Suez Canal, sparking international condemnation.\nBULLET::::- 1957 – Carlos Castillo Armas, dictator of Guatemala, is assassinated.\nBULLET::::- 1958 – Explorer program: \"Explorer 4\" is launched.\nBULLET::::- 1963 – Syncom 2, the world's first geosynchronous satellite, is launched from Cape Canaveral on a Delta B booster.\nBULLET::::- 1963 – An earthquake in Skopje, Yugoslavia (present-day North Macedonia) leaves 1,100 dead.\nBULLET::::- 1963 – The Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development votes to admit Japan.\nBULLET::::- 1968 – Vietnam War: South Vietnamese opposition leader Trương Đình Dzu is sentenced to five years hard labor for advocating the formation of a coalition government as a way to move toward an end to the war.\nBULLET::::- 1971 – Apollo program: Launch of \"Apollo 15\" on the first Apollo \"J-Mission\", and first use of a Lunar Roving Vehicle.\nBULLET::::- 1974 – Greek Prime Minister Konstantinos Karamanlis forms the country's first civil government after seven years of military rule.\nBULLET::::- 1977 – The National Assembly of Quebec imposes the use of French as the official language of the provincial government.\nBULLET::::- 1989 – A federal grand jury indicts Cornell University student Robert T. Morris, Jr. for releasing the Morris worm, thus becoming the first person to be prosecuted under the 1986 Computer Fraud and Abuse Act.\nBULLET::::- 1990 – The Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990 is signed into law by President George H.W. Bush.\nBULLET::::- 1993 – Asiana Airlines Flight 733 crashes into a ridge on Mt. Ungeo on its third attempt to land at Mokpo Airport, South Korea. Sixty-eight of the 116 people onboard are killed.\nBULLET::::- 1999 – Kargil conflict officially comes to an end. The Indian Army announces the complete eviction of Pakistani intruders.\nBULLET::::- 2005 – Space Shuttle program: STS-114 Mission: Launch of \"Discovery\", NASA's first scheduled flight mission after the \"Columbia\" Disaster in 2003.\nBULLET::::- 2005 – Mumbai, India receives 99.5cm of rain (39.17 inches) within 24 hours, resulting in floods killing over 5,000 people.\nBULLET::::- 2008 – Fifty-six people are killed and over 200 people are injured, in the Ahmedabad bombings in India.\nBULLET::::- 2009 – The militant Nigerian Islamist group Boko Haram attacks a police station in Bauchi, leading to reprisals by the Nigeria Police Force and four days of violence across multiple cities.\nBULLET::::- 2016 – The Sagamihara stabbings occur in Kanagawa Prefecture in Japan. Nineteen people are killed.\nBULLET::::- 2016 – Hillary Clinton becomes the first female nominee for President of the United States by a major political party at the Democratic National Convention in Philadelphia.\nBULLET::::- 2016 – Solar Impulse 2 becomes the first solar-powered aircraft to circumnavigate the Earth.\n\nBULLET::::- 1030 – Stanislaus of Szczepanów, Polish bishop and saint (d. 1079)\nBULLET::::- 1400 – Isabel le Despenser, Countess of Worcester, Engl