{"id": "15922", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=15922", "title": "July 27", "text": "July 27\n\nBULLET::::- 1054 – Siward, Earl of Northumbria, invades Scotland and defeats Macbeth, King of Scotland somewhere north of the Firth of Forth.\nBULLET::::- 1189 – Friedrich Barbarossa arrives at Niš, the capital of Serbian King Stefan Nemanja, during the Third Crusade.\nBULLET::::- 1202 – Georgian–Seljuk wars: At the Battle of Basian the Kingdom of Georgia defeats the Sultanate of Rum.\nBULLET::::- 1214 – Battle of Bouvines: Philip II of France decisively defeats Imperial, English and Flemish armies, effectively ending John of England's Angevin Empire.\nBULLET::::- 1299 – According to Edward Gibbon, Osman I invades the territory of Nicomedia for the first time, usually considered to be the founding day of the Ottoman state.\nBULLET::::- 1302 – Battle of Bapheus: Decisive Ottoman victory over the Byzantines opening up Bithynia for Turkish conquest.\nBULLET::::- 1549 – The Jesuit priest Francis Xavier's ship reaches Japan.\nBULLET::::- 1663 – The English Parliament passes the second Navigation Act requiring that all goods bound for the American colonies have to be sent in English ships from English ports. After the Acts of Union 1707, Scotland would be included in the Act.\nBULLET::::- 1689 – Glorious Revolution: The Battle of Killiecrankie is a victory for the Jacobites.\nBULLET::::- 1694 – A Royal charter is granted to the Bank of England.\nBULLET::::- 1775 – Founding of the U.S. Army Medical Department: The Second Continental Congress passes legislation establishing \"an hospital for an army consisting of 20,000 men.\"\nBULLET::::- 1778 – American Revolution: First Battle of Ushant: British and French fleets fight to a standoff.\nBULLET::::- 1789 – The first U.S. federal government agency, the Department of Foreign Affairs, is established (it will be later renamed Department of State).\nBULLET::::- 1794 – French Revolution: Maximilien Robespierre is arrested after encouraging the execution of more than 17,000 \"enemies of the Revolution\".\nBULLET::::- 1816 – Battle of Negro Fort: The battle ends when a hot shot cannonball fired by US Navy Gunboat No. 154 explodes the Fort's Powder Magazine, killing approximately 275. It is considered the deadliest single cannon shot in US history.\nBULLET::::- 1857 – Siege of Arrah begins: Sixty-eight men hold out for eight days against a force of 2,500 to 3,000 mutinying sepoys and 8,000 irregular forces.\nBULLET::::- 1865 – Welsh settlers arrive at Chubut in Argentina.\nBULLET::::- 1866 – The first permanent transatlantic telegraph cable is successfully completed, stretching from Valentia Island, Ireland, to Heart's Content, Newfoundland.\nBULLET::::- 1880 – Second Anglo-Afghan War: Battle of Maiwand: Afghan forces led by Mohammad Ayub Khan defeat the British Army in battle near Maiwand, Afghanistan.\nBULLET::::- 1890 – Vincent van Gogh shoots himself and dies two days later.\nBULLET::::- 1900 – Kaiser Wilhelm II makes a speech comparing Germans to Huns; for years afterwards, \"Hun\" would be a disparaging name for Germans.\nBULLET::::- 1917 – World War I: The Allies reach the Yser Canal at the Battle of Passchendaele.\nBULLET::::- 1919 – The Chicago Race Riot erupts after a racial incident occurred on a South Side beach, leading to 38 fatalities and 537 injuries over a five-day period.\nBULLET::::- 1921 – Researchers at the University of Toronto, led by biochemist Frederick Banting, prove that the hormone insulin regulates blood sugar.\nBULLET::::- 1929 – The Geneva Convention of 1929, dealing with treatment of prisoners-of-war, is signed by 53 nations.\nBULLET::::- 1940 – The animated short \"A Wild Hare\" is released, introducing the character of Bugs Bunny.\nBULLET::::- 1942 – World War II: Allied forces successfully halt the final Axis advance into Egypt.\nBULLET::::- 1949 – Initial flight of the de Havilland Comet, the first jet-powered airliner.\nBULLET::::- 1953 – Cessation of hostilities is achieved in the Korean War when the United States, China, and North Korea sign an armistice agreement. Syngman Rhee, President of South Korea, refuses to sign but pledges to observe the armistice.\nBULLET::::- 1955 – The Austrian State Treaty restores Austrian sovereignty.\nBULLET::::- 1955 – El Al Flight 402 is shot down by two fighter jets after straying into Bulgarian air space. All 58 people onboard are killed.\nBULLET::::- 1959 – The Continental League is announced as baseball's \"3rd major league\" in the United States.\nBULLET::::- 1964 – Vietnam War: Five thousand more American military advisers are sent to South Vietnam bringing the total number of United States forces in Vietnam to 21,000.\nBULLET::::- 1974 – Watergate scandal: The House of Representatives Judiciary Committee votes 27 to 11 to recommend the first article of impeachment (for obstruction of justice) against President Richard Nixon.\nBULLET::::- 1975 – Mayor of Jaffna and former MP Alfred Duraiappah is shot dead.\nBULLET::::- 1976 – Former Japanese prime minister Kakuei Tanaka is arrested on suspicion of violating foreign exchange and foreign trade laws in connection with the Lockheed bribery scandals.\nBULLET::::- 1981 – While landing at Chihuahua International Airport, Aeromexico Flight 230 overshoots the runway. Thirty-two of the 66 passengers and crew on board the DC-9 are killed.\nBULLET::::- 1983 – Black July: Eighteen Tamil political prisoners at the Welikada high security prison in Colombo are massacred by Sinhalese prisoners, the second such massacre in two days.\nBULLET::::- 1987 – RMS Titanic Inc. begins the first expedited salvage of wreckage of the .\nBULLET::::- 1989 – While attempting to land at Tripoli International Airport in Libya, Korean Air Flight 803 crashes just short of the runway. Seventy-five of the 199 passengers and crew and four people on the ground are killed, in the second accident involving a DC-10 in less than two weeks, the first being United Airlines Flight 232.\nBULLET::::- 1990 – The Supreme Soviet of the Belarusian Soviet Republic declares independence of Belarus from the Soviet Union. Until 1996 the day is celebrated as the Independence Day of Belarus; after a referendum held that year the celebration of independence is moved to June 3.\nBULLET::::- 1990 – The Jamaat al Muslimeen attempt a \"coup d'état\" in Trinidad and Tobago.\nBULLET::::- 1995 – The Korean War Veterans Memorial is dedicated in Washington, D.C..\nBULLET::::- 1996 – In Atlanta, United States, a pipe bomb explodes at Centennial Olympic Park during the 1996 Summer Olympics.\nBULLET::::- 1997 – About 50 people are killed in the Si Zerrouk massacre in Algeria.\nBULLET::::- 2002 – Ukraine airshow disaster: A Sukhoi Su-27 fighter crashes during an air show at Lviv, Ukraine killing 77 and injuring more than 500 others, making it the deadliest air show disaster in history.\nBULLET::::- 2005 – After an incident during STS-114, NASA grounds the Space Shuttle, pending an investigation of the continuing problem with the shedding of foam insulation from the external fuel tank.\nBULLET::::- 2015 – At least seven people are killed and many injured after gunmen attack an Indian police station in Punjab.\nBULLET::::- 2016 – At a news conference in Florida, U.S. Presidential Candidate Donald Trump publicly appealed to Russia to find and release private emails from Democratic opponent Hillary Clinton; a Special Counsel investigation (2017–2019) later alleged that Russian operatives began hacking into servers at the Democratic National Committee on that same day, leading to the July 13, 2018 indictment of 12 Russian intelligence officers.\n\nBULLET::::- 1452 – Ludovico Sforza, Italian son of Francesco I Sforza (d. 1508)\nBULLET::::- 1452 – Lucrezia Crivelli, mistress of Ludovico Sforza (d. 1508)\nBULLET::::- 1502 – Francesco Corteccia, Italian composer (d. 1571)\nBULLET::::- 1578 – Frances Howard, Duchess of Richmond (d. 1639)\nBULLET::::- 1612 – Murad IV, Ottoman Sultan (d. 1640)\nBULLET::::- 1625 – Edward Montagu, 1st Earl of Sandwich (d. 1672)\nBULLET::::- 1667 – Johann Bernoulli, Swiss mathematician and academic (d. 1748)\nBULLET::::- 1733 – Jeremiah Dixon, English surveyor and astronomer (d. 1779)\nBULLET::::- 1740 – Jeanne Baré, French explorer (d. 1803)\nBULLET::::- 1741 – François-Hippolyte Barthélémon, French-English violinist and composer (d. 1808)\nBULLET::::- 1752 – Samuel Smith, American general and politician (d. 1839)\nBULLET::::- 1768 – Charlotte Corday, French assassin of Jean-Paul Marat (d. 1793)\nBULLET::::- 1768 – Joseph Anton Koch, Austrian painter (d. 1839)\nBULLET::::- 1773 – Jacob Aall, Norwegian economist and politician (d. 1844)\nBULLET::::- 1777 – Thomas Campbell, Scottish-French poet and academic (d. 1844)\nBULLET::::- 1777 – Henry Trevor, 21st Baron Dacre, English general (d. 1853)\nBULLET::::- 1781 – Mauro Giuliani, Italian singer-songwriter and guitarist (d. 1828)\nBULLET::::- 1784 – Denis Davydov, Russian general and poet (d. 1839)\nBULLET::::- 1812 – Thomas Lanier Clingman, American general and politician (d. 1897)\nBULLET::::- 1818 – Agostino Roscelli, Italian priest and saint (d. 1902)\nBULLET::::- 1824 – Alexandre Dumas, fils, French novelist and playwright (d. 1895)\nBULLET::::- 1833 – Thomas George Bonney, English geologist, mountaineer, and academic (d. 1923)\nBULLET::::- 1835 – Giosuè Carducci, Italian poet and educator, Nobel Prize laureate (d. 1907)\nBULLET::::- 1848 – Loránd Eötvös, Hungarian physicist and politician, Minister of Education of Hungary (d. 1919)\nBULLET::::- 1848 – Friedrich Ernst Dorn, German physicist (d.1916)\nBULLET::::- 1853 – Vladimir Korolenko, Ukrainian journalist, author, and activist (d. 1921)\nBULLET::::- 1853 – Elizabeth Plankinton, American philanthropist (d. 1923)\nBULLET::::- 1854 – Takahashi Korekiyo, Japanese accountant and politician, 20th Prime Minister of Japan (d. 1936)\nBULLET::::- 1857 – José Celso Barbosa, Puerto Rican physician, sociologist, and politician (d. 1921)\nBULLET::::- 1857 – Ernest Alfred Thompson Wallis Budge, English Egyptologist, Orientalist, and philologist (d.1934)\nBULLET::::- 1858 – George Lyon, Canadian golfer and cricketer (d. 1938)\nBULLET::::- 1866 – António José de Almeida, Portuguese physician and politician, 6th President of Portugal (d. 1929)\nBULLET::::- 1867 – Enrique Granados, Spanish pianist and composer (d. 1916)\nBULLET::::- 1870 – Hilaire Belloc, French-born British writer and historian (d. 1953)\nBULLET::::- 1872 – Stanislav Binički, Serbian composer, conductor, and pedagogue. (d. 1942)\nBULLET::::- 1879 – Francesco Gaeta, Italian poet (d.1927)\nBULLET::::- 1877 – Ernő Dohnányi, Hungarian pianist, composer, and conductor (d. 1960)\nBULLET::::- 1881 – Hans Fischer, German chemist and academic, Nobel Prize laureate (d. 1945)\nBULLET::::- 1882 – Geoffrey de Havilland, English pilot and engineer, founded the de Havilland Aircraft Company (d. 1965)\nBULLET::::- 1886 – Ernst May, German architect and urban planner (d. 1970)\nBULLET::::- 1889 – Vera Karalli, Russian ballerina, choreographer, and actress (d. 1972)\nBULLET::::- 1890 – Benjamin Miessner, American radio engineer and inventor (d. 1976)\nBULLET::::- 1890 – Armas Taipale, Finnish discus thrower and shot putter (d. 1976)\nBULLET::::- 1891 – Jacob van der Hoeden, Dutch-Israeli veterinarian and academic (d. 1968)\nBULLET::::- 1893 – Ugo Agostoni, Italian cyclist (d. 1941)\nBULLET::::- 1894 – Mientje Kling, Dutch actress (d. 1966)\nBULLET::::- 1896 – Robert George, Scottish air marshal and politician, 24th Governor of South Australia (d. 1967)\nBULLET::::- 1896 – Henri Longchambon, French lawyer and politician (d. 1969)\nBULLET::::- 1899 – Percy Hornibrook, Australian cricketer (d. 1976)\nBULLET::::- 1902 – Yaroslav Halan, Ukrainian playwright and publicist (d. 1949)\nBULLET::::- 1903 – Nikolay Cherkasov, Russian actor (d. 1966)\nBULLET::::- 1903 – Michail Stasinopoulos, Greek jurist and politician, President 